<subSubSection id="23DB653DFFE9645FFF2AABDDFE06FA99" lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="56" pageId="2" pageNumber="55" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="6B7E36B6FFE9645EFF2AABDDFAD4F817" blockId="2.[136,775,1776,1961]" lastBlockId="2.[820,1459,1330,1962]" pageId="2" pageNumber="55">
<emphasis id="59B5EAA4FFE9645EFF2AABDDFEA7F8B5" bold="true" box="[136,257,1776,1800]" pageId="2" pageNumber="55">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="ACC14D35FFE9645EFEAEABDCFE74F8B4" authorityName="Nielsen &amp; Mincarone &amp; Dario" authorityYear="2015" box="[268,466,1777,1801]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Aphyonidae" genus="Barathronus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ophidiiformes" pageId="2" pageNumber="55" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="linsi">
<emphasis id="59B5EAA4FFE9645EFEAEABDCFE74F8B4" box="[268,466,1777,1801]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="55">Barathronus linsi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be distinguished from all congeners by the following combination of characters: peritoneum transparent, deep-set eyes not visible, eight fangs on vomer, anal fin rays 69, predorsal length 42.0% SL, preanal length 49.5% SL, penis long, slender, and lacking a pair of lobes at its base, and the ventral flexure of anterior 2-3 vertebrae. Regarding the other Atlantic species of the genus, 
<taxonomicName id="ACC14D35FFE9645EFB92A87EFB25FAD7" authorityName="Nielsen &amp; Mincarone &amp; Dario" authorityYear="2015" box="[1072,1155,1362,1386]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Aphyonidae" genus="Barathronus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ophidiiformes" pageId="2" pageNumber="55" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="linsi">
<emphasis id="59B5EAA4FFE9645EFB92A87EFB25FAD7" box="[1072,1155,1362,1386]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="55">B. linsi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from 
<taxonomicName id="ACC14D35FFE9645EFA86A87EFA15FAD7" authorityName="Nielsen" authorityYear="1984" box="[1316,1459,1362,1386]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Aphyonidae" genus="Barathronus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ophidiiformes" pageId="2" pageNumber="55" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="multidens">
<emphasis id="59B5EAA4FFE9645EFA86A87EFA15FAD7" box="[1316,1459,1362,1386]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="55">B. multidens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the presence of a ventral flexure of the anterior 2-3 vertebrae (
<emphasis id="59B5EAA4FFE9645EFC0CA8BEFC62FA17" box="[942,964,1427,1450]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="55">vs</emphasis>
. no flexure), eight fangs on vomer (
<emphasis id="59B5EAA4FFE9645EFAC6A8BEFA24FA17" box="[1380,1410,1427,1450]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="55">vs.</emphasis>
11), penis in mature males long and slender (
<emphasis id="59B5EAA4FFE9645EFABEA89EFA9CFA77" box="[1308,1338,1459,1482]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="55">vs.</emphasis>
short and thick), predorsal length 42.0% SL (
<emphasis id="59B5EAA4FFE9645EFB6FA8FEFB45FA57" box="[1229,1251,1491,1514]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="55">vs</emphasis>
. 46.5-51.0%), and preanal length 49.5% SL (
<emphasis id="59B5EAA4FFE9645EFBC7A8DEFBDDF9B7" box="[1125,1147,1523,1546]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="55">vs</emphasis>
. 55.0%). 
<taxonomicName id="ACC14D35FFE9645EFB4EA8DFFA15F9B7" authorityName="Nielsen &amp; Mincarone &amp; Dario" authorityYear="2015" box="[1260,1459,1522,1546]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Aphyonidae" genus="Barathronus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ophidiiformes" pageId="2" pageNumber="55" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="linsi">
<emphasis id="59B5EAA4FFE9645EFB4EA8DFFA15F9B7" box="[1260,1459,1522,1546]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="55">Barathronus linsi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from 
<taxonomicName id="ACC14D35FFE9645EFC66AB3EFB95F997" authorityName="Goode &amp; Bean" authorityYear="1886" box="[964,1075,1554,1578]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Aphyonidae" genus="Barathronus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ophidiiformes" pageId="2" pageNumber="55" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="bicolor">
<emphasis id="59B5EAA4FFE9645EFC66AB3EFB95F997" box="[964,1075,1554,1578]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="55">B. bicolor</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the number of fangs on vomer (8 
<emphasis id="59B5EAA4FFE9645EFCF2AB1EFCC8F9F7" box="[848,878,1587,1610]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="55">vs.</emphasis>
1-5), the ventral flexure of the anterior vertebrae (
<emphasis id="59B5EAA4FFE9645EFA37AB1EFA15F9F7" box="[1429,1459,1587,1610]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="55">vs.</emphasis>
no flexure), a transparent (
<emphasis id="59B5EAA4FFE9645EFBF4AB7EFBD2F9D7" box="[1110,1140,1619,1642]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="55">vs.</emphasis>
bluish) peritoneum, eyes not visible (
<emphasis id="59B5EAA4FFE9645EFC2CAB5EFC0AF937" box="[910,940,1651,1674]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="55">vs.</emphasis>
eyes most often visible), and anal fin rays 69 (
<emphasis id="59B5EAA4FFE9645EFC9EABBEFCFCF917" box="[828,858,1683,1706]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="55">vs.</emphasis>
46-59). 
<taxonomicName id="ACC14D35FFE9645EFC15ABBFFBDDF917" authorityName="Nielsen &amp; Mincarone &amp; Dario" authorityYear="2015" box="[951,1147,1682,1706]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Aphyonidae" genus="Barathronus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ophidiiformes" pageId="2" pageNumber="55" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="linsi">
<emphasis id="59B5EAA4FFE9645EFC15ABBFFBDDF917" box="[951,1147,1682,1706]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="55">Barathronus linsi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from 
<taxonomicName id="ACC14D35FFE9645EFAB1ABBEFA36F917" authorityName="Nielsen" authorityYear="1984" box="[1299,1424,1682,1706]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Aphyonidae" genus="Barathronus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ophidiiformes" pageId="2" pageNumber="55" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="unicolor">
<emphasis id="59B5EAA4FFE9645EFAB1ABBEFA36F917" box="[1299,1424,1682,1706]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="55">B. unicolor</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the number of fangs on vomer (8 
<emphasis id="59B5EAA4FFE9645EFB13AB9EFB69F977" box="[1201,1231,1715,1738]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="55">vs.</emphasis>
4), predorsal length 42.0% SL (
<emphasis id="59B5EAA4FFE9645EFC16ABFEFC74F957" box="[948,978,1747,1770]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="55">vs.</emphasis>
48.0-54.0% SL), preanal length 49.5% SL (
<emphasis id="59B5EAA4FFE9645EFC9EABDEFCFCF8B7" box="[828,858,1779,1802]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="55">vs.</emphasis>
54.0-59.0% SL), and by the long and slender penis without paired lobes at its base (
<emphasis id="59B5EAA4FFE9645EFB03AA3EFB19F897" box="[1185,1215,1811,1834]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="55">vs.</emphasis>
short and thick penis with lobes). 
<taxonomicName id="ACC14D35FFE9645EFC61AA1FFB0BF8F7" baseAuthorityName="Vaillant" baseAuthorityYear="1888" box="[963,1197,1842,1866]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Aphyonidae" genus="Barathronus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ophidiiformes" pageId="2" pageNumber="55" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="parfaiti">
<emphasis id="59B5EAA4FFE9645EFC61AA1FFB0BF8F7" box="[963,1197,1842,1866]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="55">Barathronus parfaiti</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is known only from a single, poorly preserved, juvenile specimen. However, 
<taxonomicName id="ACC14D35FFE9645EFA39AA7EFCC2F837" authorityName="Nielsen &amp; Mincarone &amp; Dario" authorityYear="2015" class="Actinopterygii" family="Aphyonidae" genus="Barathronus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ophidiiformes" pageId="2" pageNumber="55" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="linsi">
<emphasis id="59B5EAA4FFE9645EFA39AA7EFCC2F837" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="55">B. linsi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="ACC14D35FFE9645EFC3FAA5EFBB7F837" baseAuthorityName="Vaillant" baseAuthorityYear="1888" box="[925,1041,1906,1930]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Aphyonidae" genus="Barathronus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ophidiiformes" pageId="2" pageNumber="55" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="parfaiti">
<emphasis id="59B5EAA4FFE9645EFC3FAA5EFBB7F837" box="[925,1041,1906,1930]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="55">B. parfaiti</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are clearly distinct by the number of precaudal (33 
<emphasis id="59B5EAA4FFE9645EFC73AABEFC49F817" box="[977,1007,1939,1962]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="55">vs.</emphasis>
37) and total (78 
<emphasis id="59B5EAA4FFE9645EFB11AABEFB77F817" box="[1203,1233,1939,1962]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="55">vs.</emphasis>
84) vertebrae.
</paragraph>
<caption id="3FBE663EFFE8645FFF23AEACFD72FC04" ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4551293" ID-Zenodo-Dep="4551293" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4551293/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="56" startId="3.[129,168,897,921]" targetBox="[128,1451,174,884]" targetPageId="3">
<paragraph id="6B7E36B6FFE8645FFF23AEACFD72FC04" blockId="3.[129,1452,897,953]" pageId="3" pageNumber="56">
<emphasis id="59B5EAA4FFE8645FFF23AEACFF6EFC24" bold="true" box="[129,200,897,921]" pageId="3" pageNumber="56">Fig. 1.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="ACC14D35FFE8645FFF75AEACFE35FC24" authority="Nielsen &amp; Mincarone &amp; Dario, 2015" authorityName="Nielsen &amp; Mincarone &amp; Dario" authorityYear="2015" box="[215,403,897,921]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Aphyonidae" genus="Barathronus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ophidiiformes" pageId="3" pageNumber="56" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="linsi" status="new species">
<emphasis id="59B5EAA4FFE8645FFF75AEACFE35FC24" box="[215,403,897,921]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="56">Barathronus linsi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicNameLabel id="428657DFFFE8645FFE03AEAFFD83FC24" box="[417,549,897,921]" pageId="3" pageNumber="56" rank="species">new species</taxonomicNameLabel>
, holotype, MNRJ 41723, 101 mm SL: (A) recently collected; (B) after two years in preservative (horizontally inverted, right side depicted).
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph id="6B7E36B6FFE8645FFF04AEC1FE06FA99" blockId="3.[128,768,1004,1316]" pageId="3" pageNumber="56">
<taxonomicName id="ACC14D35FFE8645FFF04AEC1FECFFBB9" authorityName="Nielsen &amp; Mincarone &amp; Dario" authorityYear="2015" box="[166,361,1004,1028]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Aphyonidae" genus="Barathronus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ophidiiformes" pageId="3" pageNumber="56" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="linsi">
<emphasis id="59B5EAA4FFE8645FFF04AEC1FECFFBB9" box="[166,361,1004,1028]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="56">Barathronus linsi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and the six Indo-Pacific congeners differ in a series of features, which are summarized in 
<tableCitation id="2643030DFFE8645FFF22A901FF74FBF9" box="[128,210,1068,1092]" captionStart="Table 2" captionStartId="2.[136,199,174,198]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Table 2. Selected diagnostic characters of all valid species of Barathronus. * Specimen is severely damaged, therefore numbers presented are approximations. ** P = Pigmented; T = Transparent." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/3FBE663EFFE9645EFF2AAD83FC66FF5B" pageId="3" pageNumber="56" tableUuid="3FBE663EFFE9645EFF2AAD83FC66FF5B">Table 2</tableCitation>
. In addition, no species of 
<taxonomicName id="ACC14D35FFE8645FFE5AA901FD27FBF9" box="[504,641,1068,1092]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Aphyonidae" genus="Barathronus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ophidiiformes" pageId="3" pageNumber="56" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="59B5EAA4FFE8645FFE5AA901FD27FBF9" box="[504,641,1068,1092]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="56">Barathronus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have so far been recorded in both the Atlantic and Indo-Pacific oceans. Among Indo-Pacific species, 
<taxonomicName id="ACC14D35FFE8645FFE67A941FDB2FB39" authorityName="Nielsen &amp; Mincarone &amp; Dario" authorityYear="2015" box="[453,532,1132,1156]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Aphyonidae" genus="Barathronus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ophidiiformes" pageId="3" pageNumber="56" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="linsi">
<emphasis id="59B5EAA4FFE8645FFE67A941FDB2FB39" box="[453,532,1132,1156]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="56">B. linsi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is most similar to 
<taxonomicName id="ACC14D35FFE8645FFD4AA941FF62FB19" authorityName="Brauer" authorityYear="1906" class="Actinopterygii" family="Aphyonidae" genus="Barathronus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ophidiiformes" pageId="3" pageNumber="56" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="affinis">
<emphasis id="59B5EAA4FFE8645FFD4AA941FF62FB19" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="56">B. affinis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(known from a single juvenile specimen) in meristic characters, by the presence of a ventral flexure of the anterior vertebrae, and the transparent peritoneum, but they differ by the number of fangs on vomer (8 
<emphasis id="59B5EAA4FFE8645FFDA3A9C1FDB1FABE" box="[513,535,1260,1283]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="56">vs</emphasis>
. 2) and the number of long gill rakers (25 
<emphasis id="59B5EAA4FFE8645FFEF6A821FECCFA9E" box="[340,362,1292,1315]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="56">vs</emphasis>
. 20).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="23DB653DFFE86458FF23A861FBC3FE9B" lastPageId="4" lastPageNumber="57" pageId="3" pageNumber="56" type="description">
<paragraph id="6B7E36B6FFE8645FFF23A861FDDCF819" blockId="3.[129,768,1356,1956]" pageId="3" pageNumber="56">
<emphasis id="59B5EAA4FFE8645FFF23A861FEABFAD9" bold="true" box="[129,269,1356,1380]" pageId="3" pageNumber="56">Description.</emphasis>
Meristic and morphometric data of 
<typeStatus id="B47A8814FFE8645FFD03A861FCA6FAD9" box="[673,768,1356,1380]" pageId="3" pageNumber="56">holotype</typeStatus>
are presented in 
<tableCitation id="2643030DFFE8645FFE9AA841FE35FA39" box="[312,403,1388,1412]" captionStart="Table 1" captionStartId="1.[129,192,952,976]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="Table 1. Meristic and morphometric characters for the western Atlantic species of Barathronus. * From Nielsen (1969; 42 specimens) and Rannou et al. (1975; 9 specimens). ** Based on 10 specimens; tip of rays often broken." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/3FBE663EFFEA645DFF23AE95FB74FC4D" pageId="3" pageNumber="56" tableUuid="3FBE663EFFEA645DFF23AE95FB74FC4D">Tables 1</tableCitation>
and 
<tableCitation id="2643030DFFE8645FFE6EA841FE7AFA39" box="[460,476,1388,1412]" captionStart="Table 2" captionStartId="2.[136,199,174,198]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Table 2. Selected diagnostic characters of all valid species of Barathronus. * Specimen is severely damaged, therefore numbers presented are approximations. ** P = Pigmented; T = Transparent." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/3FBE663EFFE9645EFF2AAD83FC66FF5B" pageId="3" pageNumber="56" tableUuid="3FBE663EFFE9645EFF2AAD83FC66FF5B">2</tableCitation>
. Scales absent, skin loose, gelatinous and translucent, sensory pores highly indistinct. Head down-bent, slightly thicker than body. Dorsal, caudal and anal fins united. Dorsal-fin origin well anterior to vertical through midpoint of body, anal-fin origin at midpoint of body. Pelvic fins each with a single, slender ray; pelvic-fin base below hind part of operculum. Pectoral peduncle as broad as long. Eyes not visible. Mouth opening oblique. Nostrils with low rim. Opercular spine covered by skin. 
<emphasis id="59B5EAA4FFE8645FFF19ABA1FDB5F919" box="[187,531,1676,1700]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="56">Musculi infracarinalis mediales</emphasis>
yellowish white; ratio between length and height of “middle fields” (
<bibRefCitation id="0F504B47FFE8645FFDC7AB81FF28F959" author="Nielsen" pageId="3" pageNumber="56" pagination="7 - 88" refId="ref5750" refString="Nielsen, J. G. 1969. Systematics and biology of the Aphyonidae (Pisces, Ophidioidea). Galathea Report, 10: 7 - 88." type="journal article" year="1969">Nielsen, 1969: 9</bibRefCitation>
) 
<emphasis id="59B5EAA4FFE8645FFF3EABE0FF13F959" box="[156,181,1741,1764]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="56">ca</emphasis>
. 0.5. Anterior gill arch with 26 prolonged rakers (up to 2.2% SL): four on upper branch, one in the angle and 21 on lower branch. About 30 very small gill filaments (0.6% SL). Pseudobranchial filaments apparently absent. Testes large (22% SL), nearly filling abdominal cavity. Intromittent organ a 9-mm long slender penis, covered proximally by urogenital hood. Lobes at base of penis absent.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="6B7E36B6FFE8645FFCF0AEC1FAC4FB59" blockId="3.[813,1452,1004,1252]" pageId="3" pageNumber="56">
Otolith: Otolith 
<quantity id="AC399B53FFE8645FFBA1AEC1FBF1FBBE" box="[1027,1111,1004,1028]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.2" pageId="3" pageNumber="56" unit="mm" value="2.2">2.2 mm</quantity>
long, compact, with nearly flat inner face and strongly convex outer face. Outline round, with somewhat depressed predorsal rim. Otolith height 
<quantity id="AC399B53FFE8645FFA29A901FCE5FBD9" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.048" pageId="3" pageNumber="56" unit="in" value="1.2">1.2 in</quantity>
length; otolith thickness 
<quantity id="AC399B53FFE8645FFBF1A961FB28FBD9" box="[1107,1166,1100,1124]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.318" pageId="3" pageNumber="56" unit="in" value="1.7">1.7 in</quantity>
height. Sulcus moderately large, positioned centrally on inner face and terminating at some distance from otolith rims. A single, undivided, small, narrow colliculum located in anterior part of sulcus. Small bulge on inner face in front of sulcus (
<figureCitation id="F3FA2A33FFE8645FFAB6A9E1FAF3FB59" box="[1300,1365,1228,1252]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="3.[813,852,1609,1633]" captionTargetBox="[821,1446,1297,1589]" captionTargetId="figure-350@3.[813,1452,1289,1595]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Fig. 2. Sagittal otolith of Barathronus linsi, holotype, MNRJ 41723: (A) median view; (B) ventral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4551295" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4551295/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="56">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<caption id="3FBE663EFFE8645FFC8FAB64FB53F93C" ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4551295" ID-Zenodo-Dep="4551295" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4551295/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="56" startId="3.[813,852,1609,1633]" targetBox="[821,1446,1297,1589]" targetPageId="3">
<paragraph id="6B7E36B6FFE8645FFC8FAB64FB53F93C" blockId="3.[813,1451,1609,1665]" pageId="3" pageNumber="56">
<emphasis id="59B5EAA4FFE8645FFC8FAB64FCD7F9DC" bold="true" box="[813,881,1609,1633]" pageId="3" pageNumber="56">Fig. 2.</emphasis>
Sagittal otolith of 
<taxonomicName id="ACC14D35FFE8645FFB97AB64FB49F9DC" authorityName="Nielsen &amp; Mincarone &amp; Dario" authorityYear="2015" box="[1077,1263,1609,1633]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Aphyonidae" genus="Barathronus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ophidiiformes" pageId="3" pageNumber="56" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="linsi">
<emphasis id="59B5EAA4FFE8645FFB97AB64FB49F9DC" box="[1077,1263,1609,1633]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="56">Barathronus linsi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, holotype, MNRJ 41723: (A) median view; (B) ventral view.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph id="6B7E36B6FFE8645FFCF0AB87FBFDF8FF" blockId="3.[813,1452,1706,1955]" pageId="3" pageNumber="56">Dentition: Palatines edentate. Vomer with two small teeth located between eight distally placed fangs (three broken). Premaxilla with 1-2 rows of small teeth in its full length. Dentary with seven fangs on posterior half and small teeth on anterior half.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="6B7E36B6FFE86458FCF0AA67FD1FFE9B" blockId="3.[813,1452,1706,1955]" lastBlockId="4.[136,774,174,294]" lastPageId="4" lastPageNumber="57" pageId="3" pageNumber="56">
Axial skeleton: Precaudal vertebrae 33, all centrae short and high, anterior 2-3 vertebrae ventrally flexed. First vertebra with very short neural spine. Vertebrae 2-8 with long and slightly laterally compressed neural spines decreasing in length posteriorly. Short parapophyses developed on vertebrae 4-33. Pleural and epipleural ribs absent. Vertebral centrae hourglass-shaped (
<figureCitation id="F3FA2A33FFEF6458FDCEAC23FD0AFE9B" box="[620,684,270,294]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="4.[136,175,739,763]" captionTargetBox="[136,1459,457,725]" captionTargetId="figure-116@4.[136,1459,457,725]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Fig. 3. Radiograph of Barathronus linsi, holotype, MNRJ 41723, 101 mm SL." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4551297" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4551297/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="57">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="6B7E36B6FFEF6458FF2AAC63FBC3FE9B" blockId="4.[136,775,334,423]" lastBlockId="4.[820,1459,174,295]" pageId="4" pageNumber="57">
<emphasis id="59B5EAA4FFEF6458FF2AAC63FF77FEDB" bold="true" box="[136,209,334,358]" pageId="4" pageNumber="57">Color.</emphasis>
Recently collected specimen (
<figureCitation id="F3FA2A33FFEF6458FDE4AC62FD04FEDA" box="[582,674,335,359]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="3.[129,168,897,921]" captionTargetBox="[128,1451,174,884]" captionTargetId="figure-433@3.[128,1451,174,884]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Fig. 1. Barathronus linsi, new species, holotype, MNRJ 41723, 101 mm SL: (A) recently collected; (B) after two years in preservative (horizontally inverted, right side depicted)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4551293" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4551293/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="57">Fig. 1A</figureCitation>
) overall yellowish to reddish white due mostly to the underlying, somewhat darker, muscle coloration and blood vessels (mostly skin capillaries). No black pigmentation observed either in skin or on peritoneum. Preserved specimen (
<figureCitation id="F3FA2A33FFEF6458FC9EADC3FC28FEBB" box="[828,910,238,262]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="3.[129,168,897,921]" captionTargetBox="[128,1451,174,884]" captionTargetId="figure-433@3.[128,1451,174,884]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Fig. 1. Barathronus linsi, new species, holotype, MNRJ 41723, 101 mm SL: (A) recently collected; (B) after two years in preservative (horizontally inverted, right side depicted)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4551293" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4551293/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="57">Fig. 1B</figureCitation>
) yellowish white (no evidence of bleaching after two years of preservation).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="23DB653DFFEF6458FC96AC63FA8CFE1A" pageId="4" pageNumber="57" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="6B7E36B6FFEF6458FC96AC63FA8CFE1A" blockId="4.[820,1459,334,423]" pageId="4" pageNumber="57">
<emphasis id="59B5EAA4FFEF6458FC96AC63FC6CFEDB" bold="true" box="[820,970,334,358]" pageId="4" pageNumber="57">Distribution.</emphasis>
Known from the 
<typeStatus id="B47A8814FFEF6458FB27AC62FB41FEDA" box="[1157,1255,335,359]" pageId="4" pageNumber="57">holotype</typeStatus>
, collected between 1,965 and 
<quantity id="AC399B53FFEF6458FC0DAC42FBABFE3B" box="[943,1037,367,391]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.045" pageId="4" pageNumber="57" unit="m" value="2045.0">2,045 m</quantity>
depth in the Potiguar basin, of 
<collectingRegion id="A905F854FFEF6458FA29AC42FC49FE1B" country="Brazil" name="Rio Grande do Norte" pageId="4" pageNumber="57">Rio Grande do Norte</collectingRegion>
, northeastern 
<collectingCountry id="13D67626FFEF6458FB28ACA2FB6BFE1A" box="[1162,1229,399,423]" name="Brazil" pageId="4" pageNumber="57">Brazil</collectingCountry>
(
<figureCitation id="F3FA2A33FFEF6458FB7EACA2FAB8FE1A" box="[1244,1310,399,423]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="4.[136,175,1901,1925]" captionTargetBox="[136,1459,801,1887]" captionTargetId="figure-131@4.[136,1459,801,1887]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Fig. 4. Records of Barathronus linsi, holotype (triangle) and Barathronus bicolor (squares) in the western South Atlantic. Selected Brazilian states: RN - Rio Grande do Norte, and RJ - Rio de Janeiro." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4551299" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4551299/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="57">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
